PLEURO-PNEUMONIA
IN
CUMBERLAND.

Meeting
of
the
Local
Authority.

The
Cumberland
Local
Authority
held
a
meeting
on

Saturday,
under
the
presidency
of
G.
J.
Johnston,
of

Castlesteads.
The
particulars
of
the
outbreak
at
White

haven
having
been
considered,
the
infected
circle
was

ordered
to
be
confined
to
the
infected
premises.
There
were

no
other
cattle
on
thd
premises,
and
as
the
cow
was

slaughtered
by
the
owner
on
his
own
responsibility
there

will
be
no
compensation
to
pay.
With
regard
to
the
case

at
Cleator
Moor,
it
was
shown
that
the
cow
which
had
been

affected
had
been
purchased
from
Mr
Rothery,
of
Harrington

Park,
on
the
20th
March.
In
considering
the
outbreak
at

Harrington
Parks,
it
was
stated
that
Mr
Bell
was
of
opinion

that
several
of
the
cattle
were
suffering
from
pleuro

pneumonia,
and
a
half
-mile
circle
was
declared.
The

slaughter
of
the
cattle
was
deferred
pending
a
further

examination
by
Mr
Bell
and
a
valuation
by
an
arbitrator,

Mr
Rothery
having
objected
to
the
value
fixed
by
the

official
valuer.

It
transpired
that
two
outbreaks
had
occurred
at
Hayton,

in
West
Cumberland,
one
on
Friday
among
the
cattle
of

Mr
Watson,
and
the
other
on
Saturday
morning
among
the

cattle
of
Mr
Saul.
The
animals
which
had
been
in
direct

contact
with
those
diseased
were
ordered
to
be
slaughtered

and
half
-mile
circles
were
declared.
A
large
number
of
cattle

in
the
district
will
be
affected
by
the
restrictions.
The

Hayton
outbreaks
have
been
traced
to
the
existence
of

pleuro-pneumonia
at
Mealo
Hill,
the
affected
cattle
having

been
in
close
proximity
to
Mr
Wilson's
since
January
last.

The
outbreak
at
Wellrash,
Bolton,
was
reported
to
the

meeting.
It
appeared
that
the
diseased
cattle
had
belonged

to
Mr
Wilson,
Mealo
Hill,
who
had
removed
them
to
Mr

Jardine's
for
their
keep.
Mr
Wilson
undertook
to
slaughter

these
cattle
upon
his
own
responsibility.
A
half-mile
circle

was
declared,
and
as
no
cattle
had
been
in
immediate

contact
with
those
diseased
no
further
slaughtering
will
be

necessary
in
the
district
at
present.—The
Committee
having

considered
the
case
at
Mr
Speak's,
of
Plumpton
Head,
where

a
cow
that
had
been
removed
from
Mealo
Hill
on
the
16th

April
did
not
consider
it
necessary
to
have
the
animals
that

were
in
contact
slaughtered,
the
post-mortem
examination

having
shown
that
the
disease
existed
in
the
encysted
form

and
might
not
have
been
infectious.
The
Committee,
how

ever,
ordered
that
the
cattle
at
Plumpton
Head
be
put

under
restrictions
for
a
period
of
56
days.

All
these
outbreaks
of
pleuro-pneumonia
have
been
traced

upon
clear
evidence
to
Mr
Wilson's,
of
Mealo
Hill,
and
Mr

Rothery's,
Harrington
Parks;
and
Mr
Bell
in
his
reports
to

the
Local
Authority
stated
that
he
was
quite
satisfied
that

the
disease
must
have
existed
among
the
cattle
at
these

places
for
a
considerable
time.
An
inspector
from
the

Board
of
Agriculture
has
made
a
careful
inquiry
into
all

the
particulars
of
the
outbreaks,
and
he
also
came
to
the

conclusion
that
the
outbreaks
emanated
from
Mealo
Hill

and
Harrington
Parks.
He
will
no
doubt
make
a
report
to

that
effect
to
the
Board
of
Agriculture.
It
is
hoped
in
the

public
interest
that
some
steps
will
be
taken
to
enable
the

Local
Authority
to
deal
with
cases
of
evasion
and
failure

comply
with
the
requirements
of
the
law,
and
to
remedy

the
defects
which
at
present
exist
with
the
Act
and
the

Order
of
Council,
by
which
people
may
be
prevented
from

"
running
the
blockade"
in
the
face
of
the
most
stringent

regulations
that
may
be
made

the
existing
state

of
things.

infected
circle

farm

Mr
Hamlet

contracted
by

the
meeting
to
the
buildings
and
fields
adjoining
thereto,

as
